Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Van Heflin, Julia Adams, and Paul Fierro in Wings Of The Hawk
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: U-I, Universal City, Calif."WINGS OF THE HAWK" --- A Pictorial SynopsisA story of Mexican Insurrectos in the regime of President Diaz and Pancho Villa, "Wings of the Hawk" was filmed in third-dimension, in Technicolor, for either wide or standard screen. Starring VAN HEFLIN and JULIA ADAMS, it introduces Abbe Lane and features George Dolenz, Antonio Moreno and Noah Beery. From a novel by Gerald Drayson Adams, screenplay is by James E. Moser. Budd Boetticher directed and Aaron Rosenberg produced for Universal-International. The story in pictures: 9 - Gallager and Carlos overpower a mine guard and plant explosives in the shaft. As Ruiz and his army arrive to take gold to Juarez, Insurrectos open fire from surrounding hills. Col. Ruiz takes the reins of the carriage carrying Raquel and her sister, Elena (Abbe Lane), but Gallager fights him. The carriage overturns, Elena is struck mortally by a bullet, Gallager knocks out Ruiz, grabs the semi-conscious Raquel and races to safety as explosions in the mine shaft engulf Ruiz and his men.9 - Gallager and Carlos overpower a mine guard and plant explosives in the shaft. As Ruiz and his army arrive to take gold to Juarez, Insurrectos open fire from surrounding hills. Col. Ruiz takes the reins of the carriage carrying Raquel and her sister, Elena (Abbe Lane), but Gallager fights him. The carriage overturns, Elena is struck mortally by a bullet, Gallager knocks out Ruiz, grabs the semi-conscious Raquel and races to safety as explosions in the mine shaft engulf Ruiz and his men.

Title: John Litel, Ida Lupino and Stephen McNally in a scene from Woman in Hiding
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "Woman In Hiding" -- A Pictorial Synopsis; "Woman In Hiding" is melodrama with the excitement of a chase and a highly original story premise: a woman discovers on her wedding night that she is the intended murder victim of her bridegroom! Produced by Universal-International, it stars Ida Lupino, Stephen McNally, Howard Duff and introduces Peggy Dow, new dramatic sensation who was assigned this second feminine lead as her first movie role. Written by Oscar Saul, the film is directed by Michael Gordon and produced by Michel Kraike. The story in pictures: 1. Selden Clark (Stephen McNally), member of an aristocratic family in the southern town of Clarksville, is general manager of a mill owned by John Chandler (John Litel). Coveting control of the mill, Clark pays court to Chandler's daughter, Deborah (Ida Lupino). She would like to marry Clark, but has delayed because she senses her father's distrust for her fiance.

Title: Edmund Gwenn and Mickey Rooney in A Yank At Eton
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A BIT OF FATHERLY ADVICE...That's what Edmund Gwenn, as the Eton College house master, is passing on to Mickey Rooney, his student, in this scene from Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's "A Yank At Eton." Mickey as the typical American boy who is enrolled in England's most exclusive school and finds the going tough, is starred, with Freddie Bartholomew, Ian Hunter, Juanita Quigley, Alan Mowbray and Tina Thayer also featured. Norman Taurog directed, John W. Consadine, Jr., produced.

Title: Mickey Rooney and Tina Thayer in A Yank At Eton
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: MICKEY ROONEY'S NEW SCREEN SWEETHEART...Mickey Rooney gets himself a brand new sweetheart on the screen in Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's 'A Yank at Eton." She is red-haired Tina Thayer, who stands just five feet tall. Born in Worcester, Mass., she appeared in several plays in New York before going to Hollywood on a vacation. After two small movie roles had extended her "holiday," she landed a role with Mickey in the new picture, directed by Norman Taurog, produced by John W. Consadine, Jr. 1. SHE LEARNS WHAT THE WELL-DRESSED YOUNG ETONIAN WILL WEAR...And in excess, as Mickey is caught running errands for older Eton students in one scene of the picture.

Title: Claude Jarman in The Yearling
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "THE YEARLING," a story of a family of Florida backwoods folk, and the love of a small boy for his pet, is also a story of the warm understanding and human bondage which exists between a father and son.  Gregory Peck is seen as Penny Baxter with young Claude Jarman, Jr., his son Jody.  In direct contrast to her glamorous screen roles of the past is Jane Wyman as Ma Baxter, hardy pioneer whose struggle against the elements almost strangles her natural instincts of love and laughter.  As important as the stars is Flag, the deer, whose growth parallels that of his young master, Jody.  Clarence Brown directed the film which is photographed in Technicolor with Sidney Franklin as producer for Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.  The film picturization of Marjorie Kinnan Rawlings' best-seller novel also features Don Gift, Margaret Wycherly, Chill Wills, and Henry Travers.

Title: Jane Greer and Peter Lawford in You For Me
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: ROMANTIC FELLOW!...Even when disabled -- temporarily -- Peter Lawford has notions of love and romance.  Jane Greer tries to persuade him not to cut off his donations to the hospital where she works, but Peter has thoughts only of Jane.  Scene is from M-G-M's bright new romantic comedy "You For Me," the merry triangle of a doctor, a nurse, and a young millionaire.  Peter Lawford, Jane Greer, Gig Young, Paula Corday and Barbara Ruick head the stellar cast.  Don Weis directed, Henry Berman produced.  Story and screenplay were written by William Roberts.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Joan Fontaine, James Stewart and Willard Parker in a scene from You Gotta Stay Happy
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: Universal-International, Universal City, Calif. "You Gotta Stay Happy" -- A Pictorial Synopsis. Bringing Joan Fontaine and James Stewart together for the first time, "You Gotta Stay Happy" is the second picture made by Rampart Productions for Universal-International. Rampart is owned by Joan and her husband, William Dozier. The picture was adapted from Robert Carson's Saturday Evening Post serial by Producer-writer Karl Tunberg and is thoroughly screwball, one of the gayest comedies of the year. It also is the first  comedy Joan has made in four years, the last being "The Affairs of Susan." The film was directed by H. C. Potter. The story in pictures: 5. While Bullets calls a cab, Payne drags drousy Dee Dee out of the hotel, sneaking her past would-be bridegroom Henry while he checks his hotel bill. Payne now believes he is rescuing a defenseless beauty from a wolf.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: James Stewart, Joan Fontaine, Porter Hall, Percy Kilbride, Edith Evanson and child actors in a scene from You Gotta Stay Happy
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: Universal-International, Universal City, Calif. "You Gotta Stay Happy" -- A Pictorial Synopsis. Bringing Joan Fontaine and James Stewart together for the first time, "You Gotta Stay Happy" is the second picture made by Rampart Productions for Universal-International. Rampart is owned by Joan and her husband, William Dozier. The picture was adapted from Robert Carson's Saturday Evening Post serial by Producer-writer Karl Tunberg and is thoroughly screwball, one of the gayest comedies of the year. It also is the first comedy Joan has made in four years, has last being "The Affairs of Susan." The film was directed by H. C. Potter. The story in pictures: 7. Making a forced landing in a pasture during a storm, Payne, Dee Dee, Bullets and passenger Caslon (Porter Hall), who completes the strange cargo, are put up by farmer Racknell (Percy Kilbride) where they witness the strange spectacle of the Racknells saying good night to their myriad youngsters.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Dick Powell tries to wriggle through the doggy door in a scene from You Never Can Tell
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: Universal-International, Universal City, Calif. "You Never Can Tell" --- A Pictorial Synopsis. "You Never Can Tell" is a movie for those who think they have seen everything. It is literally the doggondest comedy ever filmed, telling a story of the reincarnation of animals as humans. Starring Dick Powell and Peggy Dow, it is from a story by Lou Breslow, screenplay by Breslow and David Chandler, and was directed by Breslow. It was produced by Leonard Goldstein for Universal-International. The story in pictures: 4. Rex is in a dilemma. He can't go to Ellen and say, "I'm your dog, King, reincarnated. Your boy friend, Collins, killed me." But he wants to prove it. Denied entrance to Ellen's home by the butler, Rex knows where King's entrance in the kitchen door is, so he gets in that way.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Dick Powell and Peggy Dow in a publicity still for You Never Can Tell
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: U-I, Universal City, Calif. Dick "Speaks" For His Dinner In "You Never Can Tell." Don't feel sorry for Dick Powell - just because he leads a "dog's life" in Universal-International's bright new comedy hit, "You Never Can Tell." Lovely Peggy Dow is Dick's co-star and "master" in the hilarious film which casts Powell in the role of a police dog who is murdered then returns to earth as a Private Eye to track down his murderer. Dick and Peggy are assisted in the madcap comedy by Charles Drake and Joyce Holden, the latter a reincarnated racing filly.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Joyce Holden, Charles Drake and Peggy Dow behind the scenes of You Never Can Tell
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: U-I, Universal City, Calif. "Joyce Hits Winner's Circle as Filly Fashion Plate" Joyce Holden, complete with a purse designed like an oat bag, a jockey-type straw hat with little pointed feathers hinting at ears, offers the ultimate in filly fashions. But it's all in keeping with Joyce's role in Universal-International's new comedy hit, "You Never Can Tell," in which the actress plays the role of a deceased racing filly who returns to earth as a blonde secretary. Also, from animal heaven, comes Dick Powell as a Private Eye out to get the culprit who murdered him WHEN HE WAS A DOG! Peggy Dow, starred with Powell, and Charles Drake admire Joyce's eardrobe.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Caricatures of Peggy Dow, Dick Powell, Charles Drake and Joyce Holden by artist Jacques Kapralik for You Never Can Tell
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: U-I, Universal City, Calif. Powell Leads "Dog's Life" For New Comedy Hit; Artist Jacques Kapralik thoroughly captures the zany spirit of Universal-International's laugh riot of the year, "You Never Can Tell," Which casts Dick Powell, second from left, in the role of a police dog who is murdered then returns to earth as a Private Eye to track down his murderer. Powell is assisted in the madcap comedy by Peggy Dow, Charles Drake and Joyce Holden, the latter a reincarnated racing filly.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Charles Drake, Albert Sharpe, Peggy Dow and Dick Powell in a scene from You Never Can Tell
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From: Universal-International, Universal City, Calif. "You Never Can Tell" --- A Pictorial Synopsis; "You Never Can Tell" is a movie for those who think they have seen every thing. It is literally the doggondest comedy ever filmed, telling a story of the reincarnation of animals as humans. Starring Dick Powell and Peggy Dow, it is from a story by Lou Breslow, screenplay by Breslow and David Chandler, and was directed by Breslow. It was produced by Leonard Goldstein for Universal-International. The story in pictures: 9. Taking Max to Ellen's residence, where Ellen's sea-faring grandpa (Albert Sharpe) has arrived to give her away in marriage, Rex shows Ellen that Max recognizes - and hates - Collins, too. Collins is the villain who had broken King's leg in service, framed a phony jeep accident to hide it, and was dismissed from the K-9 corps for cruelty.

Title: Claudette Colbert in Zaza

Title: Harriette Haddon, Lola Ross, and Louise Seidel on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Can-can Moderne-- out of character for a moment, these young ladies who dance the can-can with Claudette Colbert in Paramount's "Zaza" break way into a Suzy-Q, truckin', tape-and-toe routine. They are Harriette Haddon, Lola Ross and Louise Seidel, of Paramount dance director George Raft's troupe.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Waldo and a crew member on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: At last the dress-- 5. Done up to the neck in corset, corset cover, and starched muslin, Janet Waldo gets the final treatment, a copy of the dress Mrs. Leslie Carter wore when she starred in "Zaza" on the stage. Janet isn't starring in "Zaza," of course, but she plays an important role in the new Paramount version.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Waldo and a crew member on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Comes the slip-- 3. A dainty thing consisting of yards and yards of cloth and being virtually a hoop skirt without the hoops. Miss Waldo is head first in its cavernous depths. The lass assisting her is a wardrobe girl (Janet Waldo in Paramount's "Zaza.")

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Waldo and a crew member on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: The Back-breaker-- 2.-- --The wasp waist and hour-glass silhouette necessary to Miss Waldo's portrayal of a heartbroken little music hall entertainer of the 1900's whose romance is shattered by trouble-making parents is insured with a corset. Assistance of a strong-armed wardrobe attendent is solicited. Maybe you don't remember these vise-like foundation garments and the bloomers with the hamburg lace. But Miss Waldo will never forget 'em. (Janet Waldo in Paramount's "Zaza.")

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Waldo on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: First Step-- 1. --in the evolution of a modern beauty to a Turn-of-the-Century belle is illustrated by Janet Waldo, pretty Spokane miss, protege of Bing Crosby and Mme. Alla Nazimova, who gets her first dramatic role in Paramount's "Zaza," with Claudette Colbert and Herbert Marshall. Miss Waldo is shown entering the wardrobe department at Paramount to be garbed for the role, and wait till you get a load of the clothes--what we mean, a load of clothes in anybody's language.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Herbert Marshall, Claudette Colbert, and Bert Lahr in Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Herbert Marshall Claudette Colbert- Bert Lahr in "Zaza" Paramount 1939

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Claudette Colbert with film crew on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Heart Song-- Claudette Colbert finishes "Zaza" singing "Hello, My Darling" to Herbert Marshall. And here is actual filming of her doing the number, a sentimental ballad in which she was coached by Fanny Brice, who though under contract to M-G-M generously worked with the Paramount star for two days, imparting the technique that made Fanny Brice singing "My Man" an international attraction.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Claudette Colbert in Zaza
Description.caption: Claudette Colbert in "Zaza," with Herbert Marshall, Bert Lahr, Helen Westley, Constance Collier, Genevieve Tobin and Walter Catlett.|~|Text from back of photograph: Home again– Mme. Jeanne Chauchoin, mother of Claudette Colbert, just returned from a trip abroad has tea on the set of "Zaza" at Paramount with her daughter, right, star of the picture. And Martha Raye, left, drops in to share Claudette's hospitality and chat with Mme. Chauchoin who is a great favorite in the film colony.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Janet Waldo and Claudette Colbert on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Ready for work-- 6. Janet, (left) completely garbed and coiffed, reports on the set of "Zaza" for her first day's work, where she is looked over by Claudette Colbert, who plays the title role in all those ruffs and spangles. (Jane Waldo, Spokane "find," appearing for the first time in a dramatic role, in Paramount's "Zaza.")

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Claudette Colbert on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Has her cake– Claudette Colbert having her birthday observed on the set of "Zaza," in which she stars for Paramount. And director George Cukor, donor of the cake, is about to get the first piece from the dainty hands of the star herself.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Claudette Colbert on the set of Zaza
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Vaudevile is back--1. But this time in the movies, and in Paris! Claudette Colbert cracks out with a song as the music hall entertainer "Zaza" in the Paramount picture of that name. The period is 1906 and the role is the same made famous by Mme. Rejane, Mrs. Leslie carter, Nazimova, Lily Monnet and many others.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Andrews Sisters perform in Argentine Nights
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Andrews Sisters Swing Trio Learns to DanceAlthough the Andrews Sisters, LaVerne, Patty and Maxene, won international fame as a swing song trio, their first Hollywood assignment required them to learn to dance. The girls' terpsichorean efforts are combined with hot vocal rhythms in Universal's musical film, "Argentine Nights." The Ritz Brothers are starred in the production which is laid in the glamorous pampas country of the Argentine.
Description.note: (From left) LaVerne Andrews, Patty Andrews, and Maxene Andrews in "Argentine Nights."

Title: Russell Patterson and Betty Dotson examine sketches for Artists and Models
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Three of a Kind - but the coloring is different. Famed illustrator Russell Patterson was picked to sketch his ideal girl types to serve as guides for selecting beauties for Jack Benny's latest filmusical, "Artists and Models." As model for all three-blonde, brunette, and auburn, he chose reddish-haired, greenish eyed, Betty Dotson, here being shown the finished product.
Description.note: Russell Patterson (left) and Betty Dotson examine illustrations based on Miss Dotson for "Artists and Models."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Ginger Rogers in The Barkleys of Broadway
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "The Barkleys of Broadway" -- Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers, the screen's most famous dancing partners, are back together again in Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's "The Barkleys of Broadway." The new musical, their first in Technicolor, is a gay romantic story of present-day Broadway, highlighted by six big singing and dancing numbers. Oscar Levant, Billie Burke, Gale Robbins and Jacques Francois are featured. Charles Walters directed, Arthur Freed produced. Robert Alton directed the musical numbers.12. While Josh continues alone in their musical comedy, Dinah scores a big hit in her drama, although experiencing difficulties throughout rehearsals. What she doesn't know is that Josh's coaching, when he assumes Jacques' voice on the telephone, has been responsible for her overcoming her troubles.
Description.note: Ginger Rogers (left) and other cast members in "The Barkleys of Broadway."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: William A. Wellman and George Murphy on the set of Battleground
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Selection of William A. Wellman to direct Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's "Battleground," was in keeping with his brilliant record--all the way from "Wings" to the "Story of G.I. Joe," and his ability to handle large, male casts. A tireless worker, ever-ready with gag and joke, Wellman was "tops" with the cast headed by Van Johnson, John Hodiak, Ricardo Montalban and George Murphy. Dore Schary produced "Battleground," with Robert Pirosh, ex-G.I. and author of original and screenplay, as associate producer.George Murphy explains a point to Wellman during pre-production training. Wellman put the entire cast through two weeks intensive "Basic Training."
Description.note: Director William A. Wellman (left) and George Murphy on the set of "Battleground."

Title: Rock Hudson, Arthur Kennedy, and James Stewart in Bend of the River
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: The settlers reach fertile country up river, but the supplies promised by Hendricks fail to arrive. Glyn and Jeremy return to Portland and learn that gold has been discovered, that Hendricks is profiteering and has no plans to keep his promise. Glyn decides his only choice is to steal the river boat. Cole, now in love with Laura, again joins with McLyntock as does young gambler Trey Wilson (Rock Hudson) who is in love with Marjie. They have a fight with Hendricks and his gunslingers and "kidnap" the boat.
Description.note: (From left) Rock Hudson, Arthur Kennedy, and James Stewart in "Bend of the River."

Title: Cecil B. DeMille and William Bendix on the set of Blaze of Noon
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Meeting---C.B. DeMille, famous producer-director, whose name is as well known as that of most movie stars, greets the possessor of a face that is also famous throughout the world---William Bendix, currently co-starring in the Paramount airmail epic, "Blaze of Noon."
Description.note: Cecil B. DeMille (left) and William Bendix on the set of "Blaze of Noon."

Name.subject: Bendix, William, $d 1906-1964
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: William Bendix on the set of Blaze of Noon
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Rugged Indoor Flying---The life of a pilot in a movie is not always a simple one in spite of the much vaunted tricks of the trade. Here William Bendix, who plays a mail pilot given to unorthodox stunting in the Paramount aviation epic, "Blaze of Noon," is the victim as closeups of an upside down flight are photographed inside a stage at the studio. The indoor scenes matched exteriors showing a plane going through violent maneuvers. Bill stars with Anne Baxter, William Holden, Sonny Tufts, Sterling Hayden and Howard da Silva in the airmail story directed by John Farrow.(1) With a special pad around his hips, William Bendix is fitted into the rig which will hold him upside down in a stunting plane, the instrument panel of which can be seen above him. Two "wire" men, who arranged the harness, hold Bill before he's hoisted.(Please Credit "Blaze of Noon")
Description.note: William Bendix (center) and two crew members on the set of "Blaze of Noon."

Title: Virginia Dale in Buck Benny Rides Again
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Hollywood Likes casual coiffures for summer. Virginia Dale, vivacious blonde Paramount player opposite Jack Benny in "Buck Benny Rides Again," wears a very short page-boy bob with an off-face wave in her topknot. The sides of Miss Dale's hair are curved so that a single roll of curl frames her face and the overall effect is smooth, shining and easy to comb.

AltTitle.uniform: Calamity Jane and Sam Bass (Motion picture)
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Horse and rider in a scene from Calamity Jane and Sam Bass
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "Calamity Jane and Sam Bass" - A Pictorial Synopsis"Calamity Jane and Sam Bass" is a Technicolor western, a tale of the Old West when each man, and an occasional woman, carried the law in a holster on his hip. Its story is a heady mixture of guns and girls, written originally by George Sherman, who directed, and written as a screenplay by Maurice Geraghty and Melvin Levy. Starring Yvonne De Carlo as Calamity Jane and Howard Duff as Sam Bass, its other top players are Dorothy Hart, Willard Parker and Lloyd Bridges. Leonard Goldstein produced, and Irving Glassberg directed photography, the footage having been shot almost entirely in southern Utah. The story in pictures:4. When the race is run, the mare takes the lead, then falters and falls, making it possible for Calamity and Thunderbolt to catch up and win. Sam collects, and Calamity gets mighty interested in him, as a man and judge of horse flesh. The mare's owner, thinking she has pulled a tendon, sells her to Sam for $200. Sheriff Eagan learns what Sam did with the borrowed $50, decides he is a liar and a crook and fires him off the ranch. Sam leaves a note for Kathy saying he'll return.
Description.note: Horse and rider in a scene from Calamity Jane and Sam Bass.

Name.subject: Barbera, Sal
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Laurence Olivier and Sal Barbera on the set of Carrie
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Things were buzzin' in the Paramount Barber Shop when Laurence Olivier completed his co-starring role with Jennifer Jones in "Carrie," Paramount film produced and directed by William Wyler. Taking things into his own hands, Sir Laurence bid adieu to his mustache which he raised explicitly for "Carrie," while Sal Barbera, Studio barber looked on, hoping, perhaps, that Olivier would not be setting a trend, which if followed by others would doubtless contribute to a recession in the Studio's Barber Shop business
Description.note: Laurence Olivier (left) and Sal Barbera on the Paramount lot during the filming of "Carrie."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Herbert Rudley, Thomas Gomez, Hugo Haas, Peter Lorre, and other unidentified actors in Casbah
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "Casbah" - A Pictorial Synopsis"Casbah," a musical film based on the novel "Pepe LeMoko," is a Marston Production released by Universal-International. The picture co-stars Yvonne DeCarlo, Tony Martin and Peter Lorre and introduces Swedish newcomer Marta Toren. Tony Martin and Producer Nat Goldstone head the newly formed producing company. The songwriting team of Harold Arlen and Leo Robin composed five new songs which are introduced in "Casbah" by Tony Martin and Yvonne DeCarlo. The famed Katherin Dunham Dancers, Thomas Gomez, Hugo Haas and Douglas Dick are featured. John Berry directed. Nat Goldstone was the producer. The story in pictures:4. When Carlo's ruse, secretly organized by Inspector Slimane (Peter Lorre), (R), fails, Police Chief Louvain (Thomas Gomez) (C), organizes a search of the fortress casbah for Pepe. The gang leader is nabbed but freed by his loyal friends who ambush the posse.
Description.note: (From left) Herbert Rudley, Unidentified actors, Thomas Gomez (center), Unidentified actor, Hugo Haas, and Peter Lorre in "Casbah."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Macdonald Carey and Victory Jory in Cave of Outlaws
Description.caption: "Cave of Outlaws" - - - A Pictorial Synopsis"Cave of Outlaws" is a Technicolor Western with a unique angle: much of its footage was filmed 750 feet underground in one of America's most interesting tourist spots, Carslbad Caverns of New Mexico. Starring Macdonald Carey and Alexis Smith, its story and screenplay are by Elizabeth Wilson, directed by William Castle. Leonard Goldstein produced for Universal-Internationl. The story in pictures:9. Cross challenges Pete to a duel with pistols. Pete accepts, and is wounded in the arm as his weapon misfires. When he is given another shot at Cross, Cross cringes and pleads for a chance to clear his name in court.
Description.note: Macdonald Carey (left) and Victor Jory in "Cave of Outlaws."

Title: Luis Van Rooten in Champion
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: What'll You Have? -- No matter what kind of an acting role a producer may have in mind, Luis Van Rooten, Hollywood's all-purpose actor, is the man for the job. Luis plays the part of Jerome Harris, flashy Broadway character, in "Champion," which stars Kirk Douglas, directed by Mark Robson. He recently has played an army psychology, a crooked French attorney, a narcotic inspector, a sharp lawyer and a doting father.

A Paramount Picture.|~|Text from back of photograph: Real Life Roles -- Both Fred MacMurray and Harriet Hilliard have roles in Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove" that closely parallel their careers in real life. MacMurray, who came to the movies from the famous "California Collegians," plays the part of a band leader. Miss Hilliard, who sings with Ozzie Nelson's orchestra, is the songstress of the film band.

Name.subject: Hayes, Youda
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harriet Hilliard and Youda Hayes on the set of Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Another Hollywood Gadget -- Harriet Hilliard, lovely leading lady of "Cocoanut Grove," finds the "stand-up chair" a real boon after a long day of long, tiring scenes at Paramount. The peculiar chair protects the costly gowns of the Hollywood stars in their brief moments of relaxation. At the right is the star's stand-in, Youda Hayes.
Description.note: Harriet Hilliard (left) and Youda Hayes on the set of "Cocoanut Grove."|~|Harriet Hilliard is the maiden name of Harriet Nelson

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harriet Hilliard in Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Long May It Wave! - and waves it does, just as though it were flying from the prow of a speeding destroyer instead of the staff carried by Harriet Hilliard. The wind is supplied by a wind machine, but the effect is striking just the same.
Description.note: Harriet Hilliard is the maiden name of Harriet Nelson

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harriet Hilliard in Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Long May It Wave! - the setting is Hollywood instead of Fort McHenry and the flagbearer is Harriet Hilliard, lovely leading lady of Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove," but the flag waves just as bravely as it did that msity morning 125 years ago, when Francis Scott Key penned his immortal lines.
Description.note: Harriet Hilliard is the maiden name of Harriet Nelson

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harriet Hilliard and Rollie Asher on the set of Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Hollywood's "Stand-Up Chair" - Harriet Hilliard, lovely leading lady of "Cocoanut Grove" chats with Assistant Director Rollie Asher between scenes on the set at Paramount. She is "sitting" in the "stand-up chair," clever Hollywood device which permits the stars to relax without rumpling the expensive gowns such as Miss Hilliard is wearing in this informal photograph.
Description.note: Harriet Hilliard (left) and Rollie Asher on the set of "Cocoanut Grove."|~|Harriet Hilliard is the maiden name of Harriet Nelson

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Dorothy Howe in Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Veils - continue to add glamour to hats both large and small. Dorothy Howe in Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove," wears a turban of pin-pleated brown felt with a frothy veil of brown covered with chenille dots.

Name.subject: Owens, Harry|~|Lloyd, Harold, $d 1893-1971
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Harry Owens and Harold Lloyd on the set of Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Composer Autographs New Hit - Harry Owens, whose "Sweet Leilani" won the Motion Picture Academy award as the best film song of 1937, autographs his new hit tune, "Cocoanut Grove," for Harold Lloyd. Owens and his Royal Hawaiian Orchestra from Honolulu were specifically imported by Paramount to appear in the filmusical, "Cocoanut Grove," for which the maestro has written the music.
Description.note: Harry Owens (left) and Harold Lloyd on the set of "Cocoanut Grove."

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Dorothy Howe in Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: FELT -- continues to be popular in the summer millinery trend in Hollywood. Dorothy Howe, in Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove," wears a skull-cap model in brown with a fan effect sweeping upward from the draped crown.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Dorothy Howe in Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Capes - are back in various versions for Hollywood's early summer fashion trend. Dorothy Howe in Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove" wears a daytime dress of brown jersey with an interesting belt of shiny gold kid. The neckline is collarless but cut in a shallow, scalloped "V" which is repeated at the hem of the dress. The sleeves are long and bloused below the elbow over a tight cuff. An unlined, circular cape of beige wool crepe fastens at one side of the neckline and is banded in mink. Brown accessories and a muff of mink complete the costume.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Dorothy Howe in Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Metal Cloth - stresses a cool note in Hollywood's summer evening trend. Dorothy Howe, now in Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove," wears a sophisticated, draped dress of silver lame with an extremely decollete back, a swathed waistline and a panel treatment down the front of the skirt. The gown was designed by Edith Head and is complemented by a short cape of the same material, luxuriously trimmed in white fox.

Dorothy Howe, in Paramount's "Cocoanut Grove," wears a sophisticated suit of brown worsted, lavishly trimmed in blue fox fur. An ascot of gold cloth is tucked into the collarless neckline and a jeweled buckle of cut steel is used at the waist where the sections of fur join. The movie company has taken over the famous gathering place of the Hollywood stars for authentic scenes of gaiety in the film capital.

Name.actor: MacMurray, Fred, $d 1908-1991|~|Blue, Ben, $d 1901-1975|~|Nelson, Harriet|~|Lee, Billy, $d 1929-1989|~|Mann, Billy

Title: Al Santell, Harriet Hilliard, Fred MacMurray, Billy Lee, Ben Blue, Billy Mann, and film crew members on the set of Cocoanut Groves
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Close Quarters - Director Al Santell, sitting directly behind the camera, moves right up close for a shot of the peculiar antics of his players in "Cocoanut Grove." Sitting in the chair is Harriet Hilliard, entrancing leading lady, and squatted directly in front of her are Fred MacMurray, star of the show, and little Billy Lee. Peeking through the exit under the sink of the auto camp cabin are Billy Mann and Ben Blue. The requirements of camera angles often force movie makerse into tight spots like this.
Description.note: (From right) Ben Blue, Billy Mann, Billy Lee, Fred MacMurray, Harriet Hilliard, Al Santell and film crew members on the set of "Cocoanut Grove."|~|Harriet Hillard is the maiden name of Harriet Nelson

Title: Harry Owens and daughter Leilani in publicity still for Cocoanut Grove
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Sweet Leilani Comes to Hollywood - The "Academy Award Baby" is what Hollywood calls this entrancing little miss, whose lullaby, "Sweet Leilani," has been nominated for a Motion Picture Academy award as the best song of 1937. Here are Leilani, herself, and her daddy, Harry Owens, the music-writing maestro. They were brought to Hollywood by Paramount especially for the big musical show "Cocoanut Grove," for which Owens has written several new numbers an din which he appears as an actor and as leader of his own Royal Hawaiian Orchestra.
Description.note: Harry Owens (right) and daughter Leilani in "Cocoanut Grove."

Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: "Cowboy in Manhattan"After an absence from the screen of nearly two years, Frances Langford returns to co-star with Robert Paige in Universal's "Cowboy in Manhattan." During her two-year "vacation," Frances spent practically her full time entertaining in army camps and at navy bases. As a regular member of Bob Hope's radio troupe, she has traveled throughout this country and Alaska on entertainment tours.|~|A scene from, "Cowboy in Manhattan," a Universal Production.

Title: William Holden, Virginia Welles, and Billy De Wolfe on the set of Dear Ruth
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Many Hollywood headliners literally danced their way to fame. Joan Crawford, Ginger Rogers, Bob Hope, and George Murphy all began as dancers though today they're famed as dramatic actresses or comedy kings. No exception is comedian Billy De Wolfe, currently before the Paramount cameras in "Dear Ruth." Billy headlined at Europe's variety halls with an eccentric dance routine for many years before hitting the Hollywood sound stages.Once a hoofer, always a hoofer, says De Wolfe. Between scense of "Dear Ruth" he shows pert Virginia Welles how to tear off a schottishe or two.
Description.note: (From left) William Holden, Virginia Welles, and Billy De Wolfe on the set of "Dear Ruth."

Title: Jose Ferrer, Doe Avedon, Helen Traubel, and Merle Oberon in Deep In My Heart
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A Prime Donna Goes Hollywood...Helen Traubel joins the stars of the motion picture world to make her film debut in M-G-M's "Deep In My Heart" as friend and confidante of Sigmund Romberg, hero of the color, all-star musical. Her debut finds the world's greatest Wagnerian soprano not only singing such melodies as "Softly As In a Morning Sunrise", "Auf Wiedersehn", and "Dance, My Darling" but also the jazz tune of the early 1900's "Leg of Mutton". According to Miss Traubel, she's having "the time of my life."Color, Wide-screen musical romance starring Jose Ferrer, Merle Oberon, Helen Traubel, Walter Pidgeon, Doe Avedon, plus a galaxy of glamorous guest stars in the story of Sigmund Romberg and his music. Directed by Stanley Donen. Produced by Roger Edens. Choreographed by Eugene Loring.
Description.note: (From left) Jose Ferrer, Doe Avedon, Helen Traubel, and Merle Oberon in "Deep In My Heart."

Name.subject: Traubel, Helen|~|Ferrer, Jose, $d 1912-1992|~|Avedon, Doe, $d 1925-2011|~|Oberon, Merle, $d 1911-1979
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Jose Ferrer, Doe Avedon, Helen Traubel, and Merle Oberon in Deep In My Heart
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Happy Times...Jose Ferrer as Sigmund Romberg in M-G-M's story of the composer and his music, "Deep In My Heart", has fun with his trio of lovely ladies, Merle Oberon, Helen Traubel and Doe Avedon. In between set-ups, Ferrer turns stillman to take their pictures, amuses them with color slides, explains the intricacies of miniature sets, and puts on a one-man show -- just exactly what he does on the screen -- singing, dancing, romanticizing in the all-star color musical which boasts 11 Romberg operettas, 21 Romberg songs, and 21 big-name stars. Stanley Donen directs, Roger Edens produces and Eugene Loring does the choreography.
Description.note: (From left) Jose Ferrer, Doe Avedon, Helen Traubel, and Merle Oberon in "Deep In My Heart."

Title: Beatrice Lillie on the set of Doctor Rhythm.
Description.caption: For caption, refer to image ark: 21198/zz001nsdqj|~|Text from back of photograph: Sportswear-- is popular with Hollywood's younger feminine players these days. Mary Carlisle, Paramount player opposite Bing Crosby in "Doctor Rhythm," wears an attractive two-piece dress of flannel. The black tuck-in blouse is copied from a gaucho shirt and has a stripe of pink and red flannel across the pocket. The skirt is solid, inverted, box-pleats of red, grey, black, and pink which introduces on of the most novel and effective color combinations of the season. Dress from Josephy, Inc., Beverly Hills, California.

He is matched with Joe Choynski, and Vicki and the rest of the Olympic Club turn out to see Jim take a licking. They now also know that radioactivity had developed the behemoth into a monster of giant-sized proportions and that it is only a question of time when the atomic particles will eventually destroy the beast itself.

Title: Robert E. Strickland, Mickey Rooney and Guy Kibbee in Girl Crazy
Description.caption: Stamped in black ink text from back of photograph: UCLA - Arts S/CChester Nelson Collections|~|Typed text from back of photograph: Mickey's In The Middle Again...This time it's in Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer's "Girl Crazy," that Mickey Rooney gets in and out of trouble faster than ever before. He's seen as the playboy son of a New York publisher who is sent to a small desert college for reformation purposes. There he meets his favorite co-star and screen sweetheart, Judy Garland. The film presents the songs by America's favorite composer, George Gershwin, played by Tommy Dorsey and his band. Mickey and Judy head a cast that includes Rags Ragland, Nancy Walker, Guy Kibbee, Gil Stratton, Robert Strickland and Frances Rafferty. The film was produced by Arthur Freed and directed by Norman Taurog.|~|Handwritten in black ink text from back of photograph: 172|~|Handwritten in pencil text from back of photograph: 43

Title: Producer Norman Krasna holding Melinda Marx next to Chilly Williams on the set of A Girl in Every Port
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Photo by Alexander Kahle. Busman's Holiday is enjoyed by film producer Norman Krasna who seems to be enjoying his visit to the RKO Radio set where Groucho Marx, Marie Wilson, and William Bendix are starring in the gay comedy, A Girl in Every Port. The little lady on his lap is Melinda Marx, daughter of Groucho. The scenically attired lady at the left is Chilly Williams [Chili Williams]. At the right, holding Melinda's doll, is Sara Roberts, Groucho's secretary.

Title: Midge Ware promoting A Girl in Every Port
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Photo by Alexander Kahle. SSE-Pub-A7, 9, 10, 11, 12, & 13 - MIDGE OF THE MOVIES-- New York City's Midge Ware is fast becoming one of Hollywood's most popular beauty queens. She's shown here in her car hop costume for "A Girl in Every Port," RKO Radio comedy starring Groucho Marx, Marie Wilson, and William Bendix. Midge started her career as a dancer in New York's supper clubs.

Title: Assistant Director Nate Slott, William Bendix and Groucho Marx rest in between scenes of A Girl in Every Port
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: (SSE-Pub-A48) It Pays to Advertise, especially when you're on a hot, outdoor movie location and umbrellas are scarce. Groucho Marx proclaims his claim to a bit of shade between scenes of RKO Radio's uproarious nautical comedy, "A Girl in Every Port". William Bendix, Groucho's co-star, gets a fringe of the shade, while Nate Slott, an assistant director, squints in the sunshine.

Title: Marie Wilson applies lipstick on the set of A Girl in Every Port
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Marie Wilson (Beauty). Lipstick is the most vital accent in your facial makeup, says Marie Wilson, who costars with Groucho Marx and William Bendix in RKO Radio's "A Girl in Every Port." Take pains in the application and afterwards be certain to blot with a tissue. Use a brush liner to outline lips and improve the shape of the mouth. Remember, when it comes to lipstick, always wear the color not the product.

Title: Margaret O'Brien in the winner's circle in Glory
Description.caption: Text on back of photograph: The winner!.. Margaret O'Brien's filly, Glory, has just won the Kentucky Derby and here we see her in the winner's circle surrounded by Gus Schilling, Charlotte Greenwood, Jockey Gene White [uncredited], Walter Brennan and her race-track pals, a scene from "Glory," David Butler's racetrack thriller. The RKO release was filmed in Technicolor and Superscope, and marks the grownup film debut of Margaret O'Brien, now 18.

Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Blue-grass drama -- Margaret O'Brien, making her grownup film debut in "Glory," David Butler's racetrack thriller, prepares to exercise her fast filly which ultimately wins the Kentucky Derby. Behind wheel is Lisa Davis, and at right, Gus Schilling. Walter Brennan and Charlotte Greenwood are also starred in this Technicolor and Superscope RKO release.

Title: Frank Iwanaga, Raymond Burr and cast members in Godzilla, King of the Monsters!
Description.caption: Stamped and handwritten in black ink text from back of photograph:Theater Arts LibraryMPS-341-11|~|Handwritten in black ink text from back of photograph: Gojira (Godzilla, King of the Monsters)|~|Handwritten in purple ink text from back of photograph: 1
Description.note: "Gojira," the original title of the Japanese film released on November 3, 1954, was produced by Tomoyuki Tanaka and directed by Ishirō Honda. It was distributed in Japan by Toho Company, Ltd. About a year later, American director and editor, Terry Morse, along with producers Harold Ross and Richard Kay, re-edited the film and added scenes shot with American actors, most notably Raymond Burr, and intercut these scenes into the original film. This more 'Western-audience friendly' version of the "Gojira" was retitled, "Godzilla, King of the Monsters!," and released on April 27, 1956 in the U.S.A., distributed by Embassy Pictures Corp. This photograph, featuring Frank Iwanaga and Raymond Burr, was taken from a scene in the 1956 U.S. version of the film. After gaining worldwide popularity as a sci-fi/horror movie icon, 'Godzilla' spawned dozens of film sequels and remakes in the decades that followed.

Title: Jennifer Jones and Marshall Thompson on the set of Good Morning, Miss Dove
Description.caption: Handwritten in pencil text from back of photograph: Jenny JonesRobt Hutton [sic]in Good Morning Miss Dove[actor Robert Hutton does not appear in the film "Good Morning, Miss Dove"]|~|Stamped in black ink text from back of photograph: UCLA Theater Arts Library|~|Stamped and handwritten in black ink text from back of photograph:Theater Arts LibraryMPS-340-52X|~|Handwritten in purple ink text from back of photograph: 1
Description.note: Difficult to identify photograph of actress Jennifer Jones and (possibly) actor Marshall Thompson, apparently on the set of the 1955 film, "Good Morning Miss Dove." A few discrepancies emerge: 1.) The handwritten pencil text on the back of photo identifies the name of the film as such, but it lists the actor in the photo as 'Robt Hutton.' Actor Robert Hutton does not appear in this film, nor in any film with actress Jennifer Jones. 2.) The only character and scene in the film that represents any romantic interest from Jennifer Jones' 'Miss Dove' character, is one scene with actor Marshall Thompson, who portrays her love interest, 'Wilfred Pendleton.' However, both actors are wearing completely different outfits in the film's scene. 3.) The photo depicts an outdoor scenario and the scene in the film is indoors. 4.) The actor in the photograph bears a similar resemblance to actor Marshall Thompson, but positive identification is difficult. 5.) Perhaps this photograph is taken from a scene that did not make the final cut of the film or was simply an early promotional still. 6.) The number etched into the lower right corner of the image is 925-52x, and the 925 prefix does match another photo correctly representing this film in the collection (Ark Id#: 21198/zz001nt3z8), as its etched number is 925-74. 7.) Ignoring that connection, the only other possible explanation, is that this photograph is taken from a scene from an entirely different movie with an entirely different actor, yet to be identified.

Title: Candid photograph of Robert Paige and Andy Devine at the Houston, Texas premiere of The Green Promise
Description.caption: Handwritten in pencil text from back of photograph: MPS-200|~|Stamped in blue ink text from back of photograph: East-WestPhotographic Agency|~|Stamped and handwritten in black ink text from back of photograph:Theater Arts LibraryMPS-200|~|Pasted-on paper with typed text from back of photograph: Robert Paige and Andy Devine alight at Glenn McCarthy's Shamrock Hotel in Houston for the dual premiere of the $21,000,000 hostelry and the Houston oil man's R-K-O movie, "The Green Promise".|~|Handwritten in purple ink text from back of photograph: 1
Description.note: AFI lists the film, "The Green Promise," as having production dates of August 23 through early October of 1948. AFI also lists the film's release dates as: March 22, 1949; World premiere in Chicago, IL: December 2, 1948; Houston, Texas opening: March 18, 1949. By referring to the typed caption from the back of this photograph, the image is dated as March 18, 1949, the day of the film's Houston premiere.Also from the AFI listing:"The Green Promise" had its world premiere on 2 Dec 1948, during the annual 4-H Club Congress in Chicago, IL. According to Hollywood Reporter, McCarthy held a premiere in his hometown of Houston, Texas, in conjunction with the opening of his Shamrock Hotel, which was an $18,000,000 venture. More than forty "movie personalities" rode McCarthy's "Shamrock Special" train from Hollywood to Houston for the opening, which included a five-mile "torchlight parade of the stars," according to Hollywood Reporter. The top ticket price at the Houston opening was $4.65.

Description.note: Photograph of actors from the film, "Greenwich Village," (l to r): William Bendix, Don Ameche, Vivian Blaine, Adolph Green, unidentified cast member (at piano) and B. S. Pully (in background at far right).|~|Actor/singer/songwriter, Adolph Green, was a member of the cabaret group, The Revuers. The film, "Greenwich Village," marked the screen debut of The Revuers,  and although Hollywood Reporter indicated that The Revuers' "satiric sketch of a Shubert operetta" had been purchased by the studio for the film, their sequence was cut from the finished picture. The group appears only in the party scene at the apartment of character, 'Bonnie Watson.' In that scene, two of The Revuers, Alvin Hammer and Adolph Green, are also seen singing the song, "When You Wore a Tulip and I Wore a Big Red Rose," alongside actors, B. S. Pully, Don Ameche and William Bendix. The scene depicted in this photograph, however, does not appear in the film.

AltTitle.uniform: Guilt Of Janet Ames, The  (Motion picture)
Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Rosalind Russell and Melvyn Douglas in The Guilt of Janet Ames
Description.caption: Handwritten in pencil text from back of photograph: Pantages|~|Stamped in black ink text from back of photograph: Columbia Pictures Photo By Avery|~|Handwritten in purple ink text from back of photograph: 2|~|Stamped in black ink text from back of photograph: Theater Arts Library|~|Handwritten in pencil and black ink text from back of photograph: MPS-348
Description.note: From the AFI listing: A May, 1946 Hollywood Reporter news item noted that producer Virginia Van Upp's husband, Ralph Nelson, also a producer, was set to work on the film, but his contribution to the released film has not been confirmed. Various news items in HR indicate that production on the film was interrupted many times throughout the summer and fall of 1946, and that Van Upp and Charles Vidor, the film's original director, were embroiled in a bitter dispute about the script. In April, 1946, Vidor, while working on the film "Gilda," sued Columbia for termination of his contract. The suit was part of a long-standing dispute with studio executives and personnel that spanned many years. Production on the film was suspended for approximately two weeks in mid-August, 1946, after, according to a HR news item, Van Upp collapsed on the set. Van Upp was removed from the picture, and a HR news item suggested that her troubles stemmed from player commitments that forced her to begin filming the picture before the script was completed. Helen Deutsch took over Van Upp's production chores and, during the two-week production shutdown, supervised a series of script revisions and additions. A September 18, 1946 HR news item, noted that Vidor then became involved in a major dispute with Deutsch, whose supervision he was reportedly refusing. On September 24, 1946, HR printed a statement issued by Columbia production chief Harry Cohn, in which Cohn stated "emphatically and clearly that Miss Helen Deutsch is the producer of the picture and that Mr. Charles Vidor is not." The statement also reveals that Deutsch had asked to be relieved of her duties, and that Cohn insisted that she remain on the film. Vidor's suit against Columbia went to trial in December, 1946, at which time, according to HR, Vidor testified that Cohn made derogatory remarks to him and vilified his wife, Doris Warner. According to a September, 1947 HR news item, Vidor lost his suit against Columbia, and Columbia then sued Vidor.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Production crew for Hans Christian Anderson
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: S.G. 6800-C-20. The spirit of Hans Christian Andersen's beloved childhood tales, rather than his life story, provides the basis of Samuel Goldwyn's $4,000,000 Technicolor production of "Hans Christian Andersen," starring Danny Kaye, Farley Granger and Jeanmaire. Gathered around a model of "The Little Mermaid" ballet set are, from left bottom, Clave, the designer, Richard Day, Goldwyn's Art Director, Roland Petit, film's choreographer, Charles Vidor, the director, Harry Stradling, the cameraman, and Mr. Goldwyn.

Description.note: It is a postcard format.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Joey Walsh in Hans Christian Andersen.
Description.caption: Joey Walsh is, in reality, going to correspondence school while making "Hans Christian Andersen." His lesson outlines and study contents are mailed out each week from New York by the Children's Professional School, a famous school for theatrical moppets (the one that Mildred Dunnock headed.) Samuel Goldwyn hired Jean Seaman here to handle this end of it. He's winding up the eighth grade now and in June will be graduated from junior High School. Joey insisted that he not sever his relations with the Children's Professional School because he wants to stay in the class with his schoolmates, ones he's been with since the first grade. Among them are Iris Mann, the little girl that was so good in "Room For One More" with Cary Grant, and Clifford Sales of the "Date With Judy Show." SG-6800-P-56/ SG-6800-P-55

Title: Diane Hart, Sandra Dorne, and other cast members in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: In the chorus girls' dressing-room at the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, Betty Macready (Sandra Dorne, center) is reading from a copy of the Morning Express. The paragraph refers to Janet Jones, another chorus girl who has just been made the star of the show. Betty reads: .....'It's a lucky year for Janet Jones of the Mercury Theatre... yesterday a chorus girl, today a star, tomorrow a probably bride. We mustn't say who the lucky millionaire is but it looks like greeting cards all the way for Janet....Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production directed by Bruce Humberstone and starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Diane Hart, Vera-Ellen, Cesar Romero, and other cast members in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Theatrical producer John Forest (Cesar Romero) stands on the stage of the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, facing a crowd of angry creditors who have come to demand the money he owes them. In the background is the chorus from his show, Frolics to You, including (extreme left) Janet (Vera-Ellen) and Mae (Diane Hart). Frost pleads with his creditors for a few extra days in which to raise the money. Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen, Diane Hart, Cesar Romero, David Niven, and extras in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Theatrical producer John Frost (Cesar Romero) gives an order at the Bon Viveur Restaurant, Edinburgh. Frost is dining with Janet Jones (Vera-Ellen), B.G. Bruno (David Niven) and Mae Thompson (Diane Hart). Bruno, a millionaire manufacturer, is a man of simple tasted and does not appreciate the cigar Frost has given him. Frost: Now, what shall we have to start with? How about some caviare?. Bruno: Not for me, thanks. I think it's very overrated and much too expensive. A scene from Happy-Go-Lovely, the Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero with Bobby Howes and Diane Hart.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen, David Niven, and extras in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Dancing together at the Bon Viveur Restaurant, Edinburgh, are multimillionaire B.G. Bruno (David Niven) and Janet Jones (Vera-Ellen), leading lady at the Mercury Theatre. Both are the dinner guests of John Frost, who is producing the show in which Janet is appearing. Through a misunderstanding, however, Janet believes that Bruno is actually Paul Tracy, a newspaper reporter. Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero with Bobby Howes and Diane Hart. Bruce Humberstone directs this lavish backstage musical story which is set against a background of the famous Edinburgh Festival.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen, Cesar Romero, and Bobby Howes in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Theatrical producer John Frost (Cesar Romero) is dazed and speechless. He has just been presented with a cheque for ten thousand pounds, but Janet Jones (Vera-Ellen), leading lady in his show, tells him that the man who gave him the cheque is not B.G. Bruno the millionaire, but an imposter. Charlie the stage manager (Bobby Howes) looks up sympathetically at his boss. A scene from Happy-Go-Lovely, the Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor musical set against the background of the Edinburgh Festival. David Niven, Vara-Ellen and Cesar Romero are the stars. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and unidentified dancers in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A scene from the lively, haunting waltz number: One, Two, Three, featuring Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen and members of the Corpa de Ballet.In the film Happy-Go-Lovely, the One, Two, Three number takes place on the stage of the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, where Vera-Ellen, as Janet Jones, has taken over the part of leading lady.The music of One, Two, Three was written by Mischa Spoliansky and the choreography was arranged by Pauline Grant. Scenic designs, which are executed in delicate pastel shades to suit the mood of the dance, are provided by Art Director John Howell. The lilting, vivacious melody of the One, Two, Three waltz provides an excellent opportunity for Vera-Ellen to show her versatility as both dancer and singer. Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs this big-scale musical set against the background of the Edinburgh Festival.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A charming portrait of Hollywood stars Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero who appear together in the new Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production Happy-Go-Lovely, directed by Bruce Humberstone. Vera-Ellen takes the role of Janet Jones, chorus girl at the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, who becomes the star of the show. Cesar Romero plays John Frost, fast-talking, wise-cracking producer who is constantly finding himself in financial difficulties. David Niven also stars in Happy-Go-Lovely.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Unidentified dancers and dance director Jack Billings rehearsing for Happy-Go-Lucky
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Dance Director Jack Billings, who spent several weeks at the Elstree studios training a group of chorus-girls for sequences of Happy-Go-Lovely, hands around the cigarettes during a short break in the rehearsal theatre. The girls were specially chosen for their good looks and dancing ability from the chorus-lines of several London stage successes. Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor directed by Bruce Humberstone.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and Richard Todd in London after filming Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: During the filming of Happy-Go-Lovely at Elstree studios, Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen had no chance of looking round London. She was either rehearsing or before the cameras every day of the production. So when at last, after five months hard work, her part in the film was completed Vera-Ellen decided to see the famous landmarks of England's capital for herself. Her guide and companion for the day was Britain's top male star, Richard (Hasty Heart) Todd, who was himself sightseeing in Hollywood only a few months earlier. Together, the two made a lightning tour of the city, visiting such well-known spots as Piccadilly Circus, Trafalgar Square, Fleet Street, Green Park and the Houses of Parliament. Seated on the Embankment, beside the River Thames, Richard Todd and Vera-Ellen consult a map on London to decide what they ought to see next.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and Richard Todd in London after filming Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Vera-Ellen Sees London With Richard Todd. During the filming of Happy-Go-Lovely at Elstree studios, Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen had no chance of looking around London. She was either rehearsing or before the cameras every day of the production. So when at last, after five months hard work, her part in the film was completed Vera-Ellen decided to see the famous landmarks of England's capital for herself. Her guide and companion for the day was Britain's top male star, Richard (Hasty Heart) Todd, who was himself sightseeing in Hollywood only a few months earlier. Together, the two made a lightning tour of the city, visiting such well-known spots as Picadilly Circus, Trafalgar Square, Fleet Street, Green Park and the Houses of Parliament. Richard Todd and Vera-Ellen pause near Green Park to buy fruit from a typical London costermonger.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections

On the steps of the Eros statue in Piccadilly Circus Richard Todd buys a carnation from one of London's traditional flower-sellers and pins it on Vera-Ellen's jacket.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Unidentified dancers and dance director Jack Billings rehearsing for Happy-Go-Lucky
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Framed by a chorus-girl adjusting her shoe, dance Director Jack Billings is seen in the rehearsal theatre at Elstree studios with two of the girls from the chorus of Happy-Go-Lovely. Starring in this new Associated British-Marcel Hellman technicolor production are Vera-Ellen, David Niven and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen, Richard Todd, and Cornel Wilde in London after filming Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: During the filming of Happy-Go-Lovely at Elstree studios, Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen had no chance of looking round London. She was either rehearsing or before the cameras every day of the production. So when at last, after five months hard work, her part in the film was completed Vera-Ellen decided to see the famous landmarks of England's capital for herself. Together, the two made a lightning tour of the city, visiting such well-known spots as Piccadilly Circus, Trafalgar Square, Fleet Street, Green Park and the Houses of Parliament. Well, it's a small world!, said Vera-Ellen to Richard Todd when they happened to run into famous Hollywood star Cornel Wilde as they were strolling down Piccadilly. Cornel Wilde was visiting Britain to negotiate a new film deal.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and production crew members in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Last-Minute Attention. Seated on the floor, bathed in a white spotlight is beautiful Vera-Ellen. She is about to commence her solo dance in the Finale number of Happy-Go-Lovely. But before she starts to sing the theme song Would you, Could You?, there are last-minute details to be attended to by the wardrobe and makeup departments. A light touch here and there leaves Vera-Ellen as radiant and pretty as ever - all set for her part in the colorful climax to Happy-Go-Lovely.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Director Bruce Humberstone and other production crew members on the set of Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: This earnest-looking group on the set of Happy-Go-Lovely at Elstree studios consists of Director Bruce Humberstone, Script Adviser Desmond Davis and Continuity Girl Constance Newton. Together they are working out the lines to be spoken by Vera-Ellen, Cesar Romero and David Niven, who co-star in this Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen in England after shooting Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen took advantage of the first free day she had after the completion of Happy-Go-Lovely to sped a few pleasant hours beside the River Thames at Cookham, in Berkshire. The autumn sunshine flashes on her face as Vera-Ellen, seated on this old rustic bridge, waves to a friend. Vera-Ellen co-stars with David Niven and Cesar Romero in the Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor Happy-Go-Lovely. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen in England after shooting Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen, tired after five months of hard work at Elstree studios, recently spent a day in the country for relaxation and pleasure. Her first stop was the charming old village of Cookham, in Berkshire, where she lunch at the famous fifteenth-century hotel, the Bel and the Dragon. Here she is seen examining an ancient hand-made Swiss clock in the lounge of the hotel. Vera-Ellen co-stars with David Niven and Cesar Romero in the Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production Happy-Go-Lovely, directed by Bruce Humberstone.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Unidentified dancers and dance director Jack Billings rehearsing for Happy-Go-Lucky
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Those beautiful legs and features belong to a group of chorus girls appearing in the new Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production Happy-Go-Lucky. In a special rehearsal theatre at Elstree studios the girls were working out a new routine under the supervision of Dance Director Jack Billings.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and Richard Todd in London after filming Happy-Go-Lovely

Regen Street, in the heart of London, is the setting as Richard Todd buys a newspaper for Vera-Ellen. In the background is Piccadilly Circus.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen, director Bruce Humberstone, and a dancer on the set of Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Stage Four at Elstree studios becomes the setting for the Eros statue in Piccadilly Circus as the dance team of Vera-Ellen and David Lober starts rehearsing for the next shot in the musical number Piccadilly Fantasy. One the right is Director Bruce Humberstone showing Vera-Ellen the way he wants her to hands to appear in the scene. Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and Richard Todd in London after filming Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: During the filming of Happy-Go-Lovely at Elstree studios, Hollywood dancing star Vera-Ellen had no chance of looking round London.
