So when at last, after five months hard work, her part in the film was completed Vera-Ellen decided to see the famous landmarks of England's capital for herself. Her guide and companion for the day was Britain's top male star, Richard (Hasty Heart) Todd, who was himself sightseeing in Hollywood only a few months earlier. Together, the two made a lightning tour of the city, visiting such well-known spots as Piccadilly Circus, Trafalgar Square, Fleet Street, Green Park and the Houses of Parliament. Walking through one of the many ancient alleyways off Fleet Street, in the city of London, are Richard Todd and Vera-Ellen. The sign above their heads gives the date of the building as 1700.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Cesar Romero and other cast members in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: From the stage of the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, theatrical producer John Frost (Cesar Romero) looks down on the crowd of angry creditors who have come to demand their money. Frost cannot open his show, Frolics to You, because of financial difficulties, and he has asked his creditors along to see one of the numbers so that he may request more time to pay.Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero and directed by Bruce Humberstone.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: David Niven, Henry Hewitt, and Hector Ross in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Seated in his Edinburgh office, greetings-card manufacturer B.G. Bruno (David Niven) interviews one of his employees (Hector Ross), while his secretary Mr. Dodds (Henry Hewitt) stands by. As B.G. Bruno is talking, his secretary passes across an envelope to while a white gardenia is pinned. Bruno: What's this?. Mr. Dodds (uncomfortably): Er... it seems to be some sort of a bill, sir....A scene from Happy-Go-Lovely, the Marcel Hellman/Associated British production starring Vera-Ellen, David Niven and Cesar Romero. Color by Technicolor.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Cesar Romero and other cast members in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: John Frost (Cesar Romero) faces his creditors from the stage of the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh. Frost is the produce of a show called Frolics to You, but he has not sufficient money to let the show open. The creditors demand the amount that is owing to them, and in reply Frost lets them watch the opening number of the show - Mackintosh's Wedding. The creditors finally agree to give him forty-eight hours in which to raise the money. Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero and directed by Bruce Humberstone.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Unidenitified dancers in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: First of the four big musical production numbers in Happy-Go-Lovely is Mackintosh's Wedding, which tells - in terms of music, song and dancing - the story of a Highland wedding. The bride (Joan Heal) keeps up a running chase before finally leading the man of her dreams to the altar steps. The number takes place on the stage of the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, where Vera-Ellen, Diane Hart and Sandra Dorne are chorus girls in a show produced by John Frost (Cesar Romero).The original music for Mackintosh's Wedding was written by Mischa Spoliansky and the dances were arranged by Pauline Grant.Happy-Go-Lovely is an Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Diane Hart in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Vivacious brunette Diane Hart, plays an important role opposite Vera-Ellen, David Niven and Cesar Romero in the Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production Happy-Go-Lovely. Bruce Humberstone directs. This gay, romantic comedy subject is set against a background of the famous Edinburgh Festival of music and drama.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Diane Hart and Vera-Ellen in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: Janet Jones, I think you're a stinker, says chorus girl Mae Thompson (Diane Hart). Her roommate Janet Jones (Vera-Ellen) looks at her in a blank amazement. The story had got around the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, where both the girls work, that Janet is engaged to a millionaire, B.G. Bruno. Janet, in fact, has never met him, and this is her first knowledge of the rumored engagement. A scene from Happy-Go-Lovely, the Associated British-Marcel Hellman production in Technicolor starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: David Niven and another cast member in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: B.G. Bruno (David Niven), millionaire manufacturer of greetings-cards, surprises the staff of his Edinburgh store when he arrives one morning smiling broadly and wearing a pink carnation in his button-hole. As he walks through the store he presents each of the assistants with a flower. Bruno's staff are amazed at this change in their employer. They do not yet know that a woman has entered his life... a chorus girl by the name of Janet Jones. Happy-Go-Lovely is a Marcel Hellman/Associated British production starring Vera-Ellen, David Niven and Cesar Romero and directed by Bruce Humberstone. Color by Technicolor.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Diane Hart and Vera-Ellen in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: In the bedroom of an Edinburgh boarding-house, chorus girls Mae (Diane Hart) and Janet (Vera-Ellen) hurriedly get dressed and ready to leave for a rehearsal at the Mercury Theatre, where they are appearing in the show Frolics to You. Mae gives Janet a helping hand with her skirt. Happy-Go-Lovely is a marcel Hellman/Associated British production starring Vera-Ellen, David Niven and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs. Color by Technicolor. The film is now in production at Elstree studios, England.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Diane Hart and Molly Urquhart in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: A.19. Mae Thompson (Diane Hart), a chorus girl at the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, pauses with alarm as she picks up a bottle of milk from outside the door of her apartment. For there across the landing is a woman from the dressmakers (Molly Urquhart) who has come to collect the money owed by Mae's room-mate Janet Jone. The woman has evidentally been there all night. Mae backs quietly into the room again. A scene from Happy-Go-Lovely, the Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor musical set against the background of the Edinburgh Festival. David Niven, Vara-Ellen and Cesar Romero are the stars. Bruce Humberstone directs.

Name.repository: University of California, Los Angeles. Library. Performing Arts Special Collections
Title: Vera-Ellen and David Niven in Happy-Go-Lovely
Description.caption: Text from back of photograph: In her dressing room at the Mercury Theatre, Edinburgh, Janet Jones (Vera-Ellen) talks to millionaire B.G. Bruno (David Niven). Through a misunderstanding, Janet believes Bruno to be Paul Tracy, a newspaper reporter. She has just told him the story of her life, and of how she has been given the lead in the show after being in the chorus. Bruno: Wonderful, but how did you get this break? I mean, was it simply through hard work or influence or what? Janet: What exactly do you mean by that remark?.A scene from Happy-Go-Lovely, the Associated British-Marcel Hellman Technicolor production starring David Niven, Vera-Ellen and Cesar Romero. Bruce Humberstone directs.
